## 🔹 Scenario 2: Node.js Express API
Developer gives you:
- `server.js`
- `package.json`

**Dockerfile:**
```dockerfile
FROM node:20-alpine
WORKDIR /app
COPY package*.json ./
RUN npm install --production
COPY . .
EXPOSE 3000
CMD ["node", "server.js"]
```
Run:
```bash
docker build -t node-api .
docker run -p 3000:3000 node-api
```


npm install --production
Purpose: Installs only the dependencies needed to run the app in production, skipping development tools.
What it excludes: Packages listed under "devDependencies" in package.json (e.g., testing libraries like Jest, build tools like Webpack, linters like ESLint).

Why it matters in Docker:

Keeps the image smaller (no unnecessary dev tools).
Improves security (fewer packages → smaller attack surface).
Speeds up container startup (less to install).

Typical use case: When building a container that will run in production, you don’t need test frameworks or build-time utilities inside the image.


